result.execSummary:
The defendant Gabriel A. Downey was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Disorderly Conduct, a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: Reminder Notice indicating amount due mailed to defendant with DNA form.

(10:28 AM cases 21CM762, 22CM478 called.) All parties and court personnel appear via Zoom. 
Defendant Gabriel A. Downey appeared by phone.  Attorney Zebulon Patek appeared by video for Gabriel A. Downey.  Attorney Monica A Fallon appeared by video for State of Wisconsin. 
State in compliance with victim notification requirements. Agreement has been reached and is recited by counsel.
Defendant waives right to a personal appearance and wants to proceed. Court accepts the defendant's waiver to a personal appearance.
Defendant pleads No Contest to 21CM762 Count 2: Resisting an Officer and 22CM478 Count 1: Disorderly Conduct.
Defendant is advised of charges, maximum penalties, elements of the crime(s) and constitutional rights. 
Court accepts the defendant's No Contest pleas and finds the defendant Guilty of 21CM762 Count 2 and 22CM478 Count 1.
Parties request the Court follow the joint sentencing recommendation.
Defendant makes a statement.

Court orders sentences as follows:
21CM762: 10 days jail with Huber privileges or Electronic Monitoring if jail determines eligible, which may be satisfied by completing 80 hours of community service. Defendant chooses community service. Provide DNA sample and pay surcharge and pay court costs. 1 day sentence credit. Any remaining charges are dismissed and read in. 

22CM478: 5 days jail with Huber privileges or Electronic Monitoring if jail determines eligible, which may be satisfied by completing 40 hours of community service consecutive to 21CM762. Defendant chooses community service. Provide DNA sample and pay surcharge and pay court costs. 0 days sentence credit.
